        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-08T10:22:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wonder, if the accessible buckets are known, if it\u0027s faster to do n queries in parallel each restricted with dq.Eq(\"bucket_id\", buckets[i]). It may load too many entities in memory though since there could be up to pageSize * len(buckets) results...\n\nAn alternative in case modifying gae/datastore is infeasible.",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "49696a41_21d5765d",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 214,
      "author": {
        "id": 1398165
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-10T19:58:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, the recent changes in Py says the accessible buckets will always be non-empty even for admins.\n\nIt seems we have three options here. \n1) Keep using the for-loop to find the exact amount of qualified builds in order.\n2) Use n parallel queries here and then sorting.\n3) Use n parallel queries and sorting in gae/datastore.\n\nI lean to the 1st option. The current Py code uses the same for-loop and works well (https://source.chromium.org/chromium/infra/infra/+/aec30d4e667210d2e479b90dd9524c540d93a62b:appengine/cr-buildbucket/search.py;l\u003d61-78). The latency may not be as long as we think. But it couldn\u0027t be quantified now. I\u0027m thinking we keep the for-loop and in the traffic shadowing stage next week, we can measure the performance to decide if it needs to optimize. \n\nFor the option 2) and 3), the downside is as you said it may cost a lot of in-memory usage. Not sure if it\u0027s good to use much more memory vs a longer latency. \nFor 3), it expands the scope and will take more efforts and time as we need to make it generic. Also, if the lib supports IN operator, the OR operator also needs to be supports as the two are the same underlyingly. \n\nConsidering above, I propose to use the option 1. \n\n+nodir@ as the author of python part. What do you think about this?",
      "parentUuid": "440f84cf_095d1180",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fe8134c7_179b153c",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 214,
      "author": {
        "id": 1398165
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-11T00:02:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Discussed with Nodir in gvc on solving the time vs space issues. I\u0027m going to make some changes as follows \n\n1. All the PageToken in req/res will have this regex format- `^id\u003e\\d+$` which means I\u0027ll change the existing validation func (in a different CL).\n\n2. Change the `BucketsByPerm` function to directly filter on the Bucket\u0027s ancestor key if project is non-empty.\n\n3. Use n parallel queries to fetch qualified Build keys (n equals len(buckets)); Sorting the results; fetch the desired pageSize builds (which will be done in this CL). As for the NextPageToken, we no longer know the correct datastore cursor due to concurrent queries. That\u0027s why we change the pagetoken format to `id\u003exxxx`. \n\n4. After this CL, we also need to check if build.status equals query.status when fetching and converting build model to build proto. Because the status indexes in db may be stale, i.e. the build.status has changed while the corresponding status index hasn\u0027t been updated in time.",
      "parentUuid": "49696a41_21d5765d",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "58b09199_168e0a7c",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 214,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-12T17:21:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Regarding option #3, does implementing OR really mean gae/datastore just does n parallel queries for you? If gae/datastore would still be doing n queries then I agree with the current approach, but if implementing OR means executing one query (i.e. ndb engine itself supports OR) then I think it\u0027s superior even though it takes more time to implement it correctly and generically. We\u0027ve had to modify gae/datastore package itself in the past to unblock Buildbucket.",
      "parentUuid": "fe8134c7_179b153c",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
